545. istuc ‘that which you Say’. -— Campans ‘pro Campa- num’ is attested by Nonius p. 486, 24 and by A: Brix justly compares Picens and Pi cenas.— The unfortunate inhabitants of Capua had, aiter an unsuccess- ful rebellion, experienced the full rigour of the Roman se- ate, and a. 211 (at least twenty years before the performance of the Trinummus) a considerable number of citizens had been sold as slaves. The taunt im- plied in the present passage is very bitter and unfeeling : Philto says that now (iam, after the lapse of twenty years) the for- merly luxurious inhabitants oi Capua have become so inured to the degrading treatment of slaves and to hard work as to surpass even the Syriam—See also Mommsen, H. oi Rome 1 (339 (sec. ed.)
